                <head>346. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On August 21, during a discussion at the Secretary’s Staff meeting, the subject
                    of economic aid to Turkey was raised. According to the notes of the meeting:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Mr. <persName corresp="#p_AGV1">Allen</persName> said that a full scale
                            drive by the Turks is under way for increased economic aid. The Turks
                            reportedly were counting on help from <persName corresp="#p_RCB1"
                                >Clarence Randall</persName> and Thomas Dewey. Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_MRD1">Murphy</persName> asked whether Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_RCB1">Randall</persName> had made any specific
                            recommendations and expressed the wish that the U.S. could do something
                            more for the Turks than already had been done. Mr. <persName
                                corresp="#p_AGV1">Allen</persName> replied there had been no
                            specific recommendations, with the exception that the Turks were asked
                            to put their economic house in order.” (Department of State, Secretary’s
                            Staff Meetings: Lot 63 D 75)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
